"created_at": "2021-12-10T22:37:25Z", "updated_at": "2021-12-10T22:37:25Z", "author_association": "COLLABORATOR", "body": "Interesting problem! So it seems to boil down to the question \"does the hash set store the elements in a canonical order?\". If yes, we can iterate over the elements without explicitly sorting them. Otherwise, yes, sorting them explicitly is probably the best approach.\r\n\r\nSo we do need to sort for vector<int>, but not for DynamicBitset. "author_association": "NONE", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "I've tinkered around a little and created a modifier for the `{{ wind_speed }}` field. This replaces the need i.e. for a custom `{{speed_bft}}` field.\r\n\r\nNow you can convert to speed units on the fly like so:\r\n\r\n`{{ wind_speed | unit:{unit} }}`\r\n\r\nreplace `{unit}` with one of the following to convert or remove the modifier for default units\r\n\r\nfor metric units (_no ms since it's the default_)\r\n- `kmh`\r\n- `mph`\r\n- `bft`\r\n\r\nfor imperial units (_no mph since it's the default_)\r\n- `kmh`\r\n- `ms`\r\n- `bft`\r\n\r\n\r\nTo register it in `ServiceProvider.php` just add\r\n\r\n````php \r\nuse Vannut\\StatamicWeather\\Modifiers\\ConvertSpeedToUnitModifier;\r\n\r\nprotected $modifiers = [\r\n        ConvertSpeedToUnitModifier::class,\r\n    ];\r\n````\r\n\r\nAnd for the modifier itself create the file `src\\Modifiers\\ConvertSpeedToUnitModifier.php`\r\n\r\n````php \r\n<?php\r\n\r\nnamespace Vannut\\StatamicWeather\\Modifiers;\r\n\r\nuse Statamic\\Modifiers\\Modifier;\r\nuse Vannut\\StatamicWeather\\Settings;\r\n\r\nclass ConvertSpeedToUnitModifier extends Modifier\r\n{\r\n    protected static $handle = 'unit';\r\n\r\n    public function index($value, $params, $context)\r\n    {\r\n        // Get the default units set in the control panel from which to convert\r\n        $config = (new Settings)->get();\r\n        $currentUnits = $config->get('units','metric');\r\n        $targetUnits = '';\r\n        $result;\r\n\r\n        if ($param = array_get($params, 0)) {\r\n            // Either get the variable from the context, or if it doesn't exist,\r\n            // use the parameter itself - we'll assume its a number.\r\n            $targetUnits = array_get($context, $param, $param);\r\n        }\r\n\r\n\r\n        if($currentUnits == 'metric')\r\n        {\r\n            if($targetUnits=='kmh')\r\n            {\r\n                $result=round($value*3.6,2);\r\n            }\r\n            elseif ($targetUnits=='mph'){\r\n                $result=round($value*2.237,2);\r\n            }\r\n            elseif($targetUnits=='bft')\r\n            {\r\n                if ($value < 0.3)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 0;\r\n                } else if ($value < 1.6)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 1;\r\n                } else if ($value < 3.4)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 2;\r\n                } else if ($value < 5.5)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 3;\r\n                } else if ($value < 8)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 4;\r\n                } else if ($value < 10.8)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 5;\r\n                } else if ($value < 13.9)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 6;\r\n                } else if ($value < 17.2)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 7;\r\n                } else if ($value < 20.8)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 8;\r\n                } else if ($value < 24.5)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 9;\r\n                } else if ($value < 28.5)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 10;\r\n                } else if ($value < 32.6)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 11;\r\n                } else\r\n                {\r\n                    return 12;\r\n                }\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n        else {\r\n            if($targetUnits=='kmh')\r\n            {\r\n                $result=round($value*1.609,2);\r\n            }\r\n            elseif ($targetUnits=='ms'){\r\n                $result=round($value/2.237,2);\r\n            }\r\n            elseif($targetUnits=='bft')\r\n            {\r\n                if ($value < 1)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 0;\r\n                } else if ($value < 4)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 1;\r\n                } else if ($value < 8)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 2;\r\n                } else if ($value < 13)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 3;\r\n                } else if ($value < 19)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 4;\r\n                } else if ($value < 25)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 5;\r\n                } else if ($value < 32)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 6;\r\n                } else if ($value < 39)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 7;\r\n                } else if ($value < 47)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 8;\r\n                } else if ($value < 54)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 9;\r\n                } else if ($value < 64)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 10;\r\n                } else if ($value < 73)\r\n                {\r\n                    return 11;\r\n                } else\r\n                {\r\n                    return 12;\r\n                }\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        return $result;\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```` \r\n\r\nIt's nothing too fancy, but it works :)", "reactions": {"url": "body": "I've created separate functions for each speed unit now, to DRY up the to `switch` statements. I'm not quite sure about it, so let me know what you think. The modifier stays untouched by this.\r\n\r\nIn `ConverstionTrait.php`\r\n\r\n````php\r\n\r\n    private function speedToUnit($speed, $measurement, $to)\r\n    {\r\n        switch ($to)\r\n        {\r\n            case 'kmh':\r\n                $convertedSpeed = $this->speedToKmh($speed,$measurement);\r\n                break;\r\n            case 'mph':\r\n                $convertedSpeed = $this->speedToMph($speed,$measurement);\r\n                break;\r\n            case 'bft':\r\n                $convertedSpeed = $this->speedToBft($speed,$measurement);\r\n                break;\r\n            case 'ms':\r\n                $convertedSpeed = $this->speedtToMs($speed,$measurement);\r\n                break;\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        return $convertedSpeed;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    private function speedtToMs($speed, $measurement)\r\n    {\r\n        if ($measurement == 'metric')\r\n        {\r\n            return $speed;\r\n        } else\r\n        {\r\n            return round($speed / 2.237, 2);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    private function speedToMph($speed, $measurement)\r\n    {\r\n        if ($measurement == 'metric')\r\n        {\r\n            return round($speed * 2.237, 2);\r\n        } else\r\n        {\r\n            return $speed;\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    private function speedToKmh($speed, $measurement)\r\n    {\r\n        if ($measurement == 'metric')\r\n        {\r\n            return round($speed * 3.6, 2);\r\n        } else\r\n        {\r\n            return round($speed * 1.609, 2);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    private function speedToBft($speed, $measurement)\r\n    {\r\n        if ($measurement == 'metric')\r\n        {\r\n            return $this->msToBft($speed);\r\n        } else\r\n        {\r\n            return $this->mphToBft($speed);\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n````", "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/vannut/statamic-weather-addon/issues/comments/991350427/reactions",      ...state.activeFetches,\n+                    [action.queryHash]: true\n+                }\n+            }\n+        }\n+        case 'setData': {\n+            return {\n+ }), [state.data, state.activeFetches])\n+    const fetch = useMemo(() => ((query: QueryType) => {\n+        const h = queryHash(query)\n+        const val = state.data[h]\n+        if (val !== matrix, multiply } from 'mathjs'\n+import React, { FunctionComponent, useCallback, useMemo } from 'react'\n+import TimeScrollView, { TimeScrollViewPanel, use1dTimeToPixelMatrix, usePanelDimensions, usePixelsPerSecond } from '../RasterPlot/TimeScrollView/TimeScrollView'\n+import { EpochData, EpochsViewData } from './EpochsViewData'\n+\n+type Props = {\n+    data: EpochsViewData\n+    width: number\n+    height: number\n+}\n+\n+type PanelProps = {\n+    pixelZero: number\n+    dimensions: {\n+        dimensionIndex: number\n+        dimensionLabel: string\n+        pixelTimes: number[]\n+        pixelValues: number[]\n+    }[]\n+}\n+\n+const margins = {\n+    left: 30,\n+    right: 20,\n+    top: 20,\n+    bottom: 50\n+}\n+\n+const panelSpacing = 4\n+\n+const EpochsView: FunctionComponent<Props> = ({data, width, height}) => {\n+    const {visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds } = useTimeRange()\n+\n+    // Compute the per-panel pixel drawing area dimensions.\n+    const panelCount = 1\n+    const { panelWidth, panelHeight } = usePanelDimensions(width, height, panelCount, panelSpacing, margins)\n+    const pixelsPerSecond = usePixelsPerSecond(panelWidth, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds)\n+\n+    const { epochs } = data\n+\n+    // Here we convert the native (time-based spike registry) data to pixel dimensions based on the per-panel allocated space.\n+    const timeToPixelMatrix = use1dTimeToPixelMatrix(pixelsPerSecond, visibleTimeStartSeconds)\n+\n+    const pixelEpochs = useMemo(() => { \n+        const ret: {startPixel: number, endPixel: number, epoch: EpochData}[] = []\n+        for (let epoch of epochs) {\n+            if ((epoch.startTime <= visibleTimeEndSeconds) && (epoch.endTime >= visibleTimeStartSeconds)) {\n+                const augmentedTimes = matrix([[epoch.startTime, epoch.endTime], new Array(2).fill(1) ])\n+                const pixelTimes = multiply(timeToPixelMatrix, augmentedTimes).valueOf() as number[]\n+                ret.push({\n+                    startPixel: pixelTimes[0],\n+                    endPixel: pixelTimes[1],\n+                    epoch\n+                })\n+            }\n+        }\n+        return ret\n+    }, [epochs, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds, timeToPixelMatrix])\n+\n+    const paintPanel = useCallback((context: CanvasRenderingContext2D, props: PanelProps) => {\n+        context.clearRect(0, 0, panelWidth, panelHeight)\n+        for (let E of pixelEpochs) {\n+            context.fillStyle = 'lightgray'\n+            context.strokeStyle = 'gray'\n+            context.fillRect(E.startPixel, 0, E.endPixel - E.startPixel, panelHeight)\n+            context.strokeRect(E.startPixel, 0, E.endPixel - E.startPixel, panelHeight)\n+            context.fillStyle = 'black'\n+            context.fillText(E.epoch.label, Math.max(E.startPixel, 0) + 10, 20)", "path": "src/views/Epochs/EpochsView.tsx", "position": 69, suggests that it's actually pretty expensive to do state changes to the context drawing settings. So counterintuitively, it's supposedly more performant to iterate over the data multiple times rather than toggling back and forth between drawing settings.\r\n\r\nThere's little enough data here that it will never matter, and this code is easier to read. FetchSegmentQuery = {\n+    type: 'fetchSegment'\n+    segmentNumber: number\n+    segmentSize: number\n+    downsampleFactor: number\n+}\n+\n+type Props = {\n+    fetchSegment: (query: FetchSegmentQuery) => Promise<number[][]>\n+    startTimeSec: number\n+    endTimeSec: number\n+    samplingFrequency: number\n+    numPositions: number\n+    segmentSize: number\n+ 50\n+}\n+\n+const panelSpacing = 4\n+\n+const usePositionPdfDataModel = (fetchSegment: (q: FetchSegmentQuery) => Promise<number[][]>, numTimepoints: number, numPositions: number, segmentSize: number, multiscaleFactor: number) => {\n+    const fetchSegmentCache = useFetchCache<FetchSegmentQuery>(fetchSegment)\n+    const get = useCallback((i1: number, i2: number, downsampleFactor: number) => {\n+        const s1 = Math.floor(i1 / segmentSize)\n+        const s2 = Math.ceil(i2 / segmentSize)\n+        if (s2 - s1 + 1 >= 8) return undefined\n+        // if (downsampleFactor > 9) return undefined\n+        const ret = allocate2d(i2 - i1, numPositions, undefined)\n+        for (let s = s1; s < s2; s++) {\n+            const S = fetchSegmentCache.get({type: 'fetchSegment', segmentNumber: s, segmentSize, downsampleFactor})\n+            if (S) {\n+                for (let i = 0; i < S.length; i++) {\n+                    const j = s * segmentSize - i1 + i\n+                    if ((0 <= j) && (j < i2 - i1)) {\n+                        for (let p = 0; p < numPositions; p++) {\n+                            ret[j][p] = S[i][p]\n+                        }\n+                    }\n+                }\n+            }\n+        }\n+        return ret\n+    }, [fetchSegmentCache, numPositions, segmentSize])\n+    return {\n+        get,\n+        numTimepoints,\n+        numPositions,\n+        segmentSize,\n+        multiscaleFactor\n+    }\n+}\n+\n+const PositionPdfPlotWidget: FunctionComponent<Props> = ({fetchSegment, startTimeSec, endTimeSec, samplingFrequency, numPositions, segmentSize, multiscaleFactor, width, height}) => {\n+    useRecordingSelectionTimeInitialization(startTimeSec, endTimeSec)\n+    const { visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds } = useTimeRange()\n+    const numTimepoints = Math.floor((endTimeSec - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency)\n+    const dataModel = usePositionPdfDataModel(fetchSegment, numTimepoints, numPositions, segmentSize, multiscaleFactor)\n+\n+    const {visibleValues, t1, t2} = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleTimeStartSeconds) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        if (!visibleTimeEndSeconds) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        const i1 = Math.max(0, Math.floor((visibleTimeStartSeconds - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency))\n+        const i2 = Math.min(dataModel.numTimepoints, Math.ceil((visibleTimeEndSeconds - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency))\n+        if (i2 <= i1) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        let downsampleFactor = 1\n+        while ((i2 - i1) / downsampleFactor > 1000) {\n+            downsampleFactor *= dataModel.multiscaleFactor\n+        }\n+        const j1 = Math.floor(i1 / downsampleFactor)\n+        const j2 = Math.ceil(i2 / downsampleFactor)\n+        const visibleValues = dataModel.get(j1, j2, downsampleFactor)\n+        const t1 = startTimeSec + j1 * downsampleFactor / samplingFrequency\n+        const t2 = startTimeSec + j2 * downsampleFactor / samplingFrequency\n+        return {visibleValues, t1, t2}\n+    }, [dataModel, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds, startTimeSec, samplingFrequency])\n+\n+    const panelCount = 1\n+    const { panelWidth, panelHeight } = usePanelDimensions(width, height, panelCount, panelSpacing, margins)\n+    const pixelsPerSecond = usePixelsPerSecond(panelWidth, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds)\n+    const timeToPixelMatrix = use1dTimeToPixelMatrix(pixelsPerSecond, visibleTimeStartSeconds)\n+\n+    const pixelTimes = useMemo(() => {\n+        const augmentedVisibleTimesMatrix = matrix([ [t1, t2], new Array(2).fill(1) ])\n+        return multiply(timeToPixelMatrix, augmentedVisibleTimesMatrix).valueOf() as number[]\n+    }, [t1, t2, timeToPixelMatrix])\n+\n+    const {minValue, maxValue} = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleValues) return {minValue: 0, maxValue: 0}\n+        return {\n+            minValue: min(visibleValues.map(a => (min(a)))),\n+            maxValue: max(visibleValues.map(a => (max(a)))),\n+        }\n+    }, [visibleValues])\n+\n+    const imageData = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleValues) return undefined\n+        if (minValue === undefined) return undefined\n+        if (maxValue === undefined) return undefined\n+        const N1 = visibleValues.length\n+        const N2 = visibleValues[0].length\n+        const imageData = new ImageData(N1, N2)\n+        let i = 0\n+        for (let i2=0; i2<N2; i2++) {\n+            for (let i1=0; i1<N1; i1++) {\n+                const vv = visibleValues[i1][N2 - 1 - i2]\n+                if (vv !== undefined) {\n+                    const v = (vv - minValue) / (maxValue - minValue)\n+                    const col = colorForValue(v)\n+                    imageData.data[i + 0] = col[0]\n+                    imageData.data[i + 1] = col[1]\n+                    imageData.data[i + 2] = col[2]\n+                    imageData.data[i + 3] = 255\n+                }\n+                else {\n+                    imageData.data[i + 0] = 0\n+                    imageData.data[i + 1] = 0\n+                    imageData.data[i + 2] = 0\n+                    imageData.data[i + 3] = 0\n+                }\n+                i += 4\n+      const s1 = Math.floor(i1 / segmentSize)\n+        const s2 = Math.ceil(i2 / segmentSize)\n+        if (s2 - s1 + 1 >= 8) return undefined\n+        // if (downsampleFactor > 9) return undefined\n+        const ret = allocate2d(i2 - i1, numPositions, undefined)\n+        for (let s = s1; s < s2; s++) {\n+            const S = fetchSegmentCache.get({type: 'fetchSegment', segmentNumber: s, segmentSize, downsampleFactor})\n+            if (S) {\n+                for (let i = 0; i < S.length; i++) {\n+                    const j = s * segmentSize - i1 + i\n+      }\n+                }\n+            }\n+        }\n+        return ret\n+    }, [fetchSegmentCache, numPositions, segmentSize])\n+    return {\n+        get,\n+        numTimepoints,\n+        numPositions,\n+        segmentSize,\n+        multiscaleFactor\n+    }\n+}\n+\n+const PositionPdfPlotWidget: FunctionComponent<Props> = ({fetchSegment, startTimeSec, endTimeSec, samplingFrequency, numPositions, segmentSize, multiscaleFactor, width, height}) => {\n+    useRecordingSelectionTimeInitialization(startTimeSec, endTimeSec)\n+    const { visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds } = useTimeRange()\n+    const numTimepoints = Math.floor((endTimeSec - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency)\n+    const dataModel = usePositionPdfDataModel(fetchSegment, numTimepoints, numPositions, segmentSize, multiscaleFactor)\n+\n+    const {visibleValues, t1, t2} = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleTimeStartSeconds) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        if (!visibleTimeEndSeconds) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        const i1 = Math.max(0, Math.floor((visibleTimeStartSeconds - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency))\n+        const i2 = Math.min(dataModel.numTimepoints, Math.ceil((visibleTimeEndSeconds - startTimeSec) * samplingFrequency))\n+        if (i2 <= i1) return {visibleValues: undefined, t1: 0, t2: 0}\n+        let downsampleFactor = 1\n+        while ((i2 - i1) / downsampleFactor > 1000) {\n+            downsampleFactor *= dataModel.multiscaleFactor\n+        }\n+        const j1 = Math.floor(i1 / downsampleFactor)\n+        const j2 = Math.ceil(i2 / downsampleFactor)\n+        const visibleValues = dataModel.get(j1, j2, downsampleFactor)\n+        const t1 = startTimeSec + j1 * downsampleFactor / samplingFrequency\n+        const t2 = startTimeSec + j2 * downsampleFactor / samplingFrequency\n+        return {visibleValues, t1, t2}\n+    }, [dataModel, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds, startTimeSec, samplingFrequency])\n+\n+    const panelCount = 1\n+    const { panelWidth, panelHeight } = usePanelDimensions(width, height, panelCount, panelSpacing, margins)\n+    const pixelsPerSecond = usePixelsPerSecond(panelWidth, visibleTimeStartSeconds, visibleTimeEndSeconds)\n+    const timeToPixelMatrix = use1dTimeToPixelMatrix(pixelsPerSecond, visibleTimeStartSeconds)\n+\n+    const pixelTimes = useMemo(() => {\n+        const augmentedVisibleTimesMatrix = matrix([ [t1, t2], new Array(2).fill(1) ])\n+        return multiply(timeToPixelMatrix, augmentedVisibleTimesMatrix).valueOf() as number[]\n+    }, [t1, t2, timeToPixelMatrix])\n+\n+    const {minValue, maxValue} = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleValues) return {minValue: 0, maxValue: 0}\n+        return {\n+            minValue: min(visibleValues.map(a => (min(a)))),\n+            maxValue: max(visibleValues.map(a => (max(a)))),\n+        }\n+    }, [visibleValues])\n+\n+    const imageData = useMemo(() => {\n+        if (!visibleValues) return undefined\n+        if (minValue === undefined) return undefined\n+        if (maxValue What I know is, almost 60% of my witnesses are dropped for most of my miners. Maybe you experts can re-read the code to see potential issues better than me. I can also say that this problem started about 1 month ago, with the efforts started to introduce pocv11. However, I don't have a long history in the network. In early October, either my devices were performing better, or I wasn't focused too much on this.\r\n\r\nI think there is a bug somewhere in miner_poc_statem code or in validator code, which is affecting my miners and potentially many others.\r\n\r\nPlease take into consideration my analysis and focus on finding this issue. code-block:: bash\n \n-Open a new terminal, and navigate to the ``application-javascript`` folder.\n+  cd asset-transfer-basic/application-gateway-typescript\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+This directory contains a sample program developed using the Hyperledger Fabric client API for Node.\n \n-  cd asset-transfer-basic/application-javascript\n+Run the following command to install the dependencies and build the application. It may take some time to complete:\n \n-This directory contains sample programs that were developed using the Fabric\n-SDK for Node.js. Run the following command to install the application dependencies.\n-It may take up to a minute to complete:\n-\n-.. code:: bash\n+.. code-block:: bash\n \n   npm install\n \n-This process is installing the key application dependencies defined in the application's\n-``package.json``. The most important of which is the ``fabric-network`` Node.js module;\n-it enables an application to use identities, wallets, and gateways to connect to\n-channels, submit transactions, and wait for notifications. This tutorial also\n-uses the ``fabric-ca-client`` module to enroll users with their respective\n-certificate authorities, generating a valid identity which is then used by\n-the ``fabric-network`` module to interact with the blockchain network.\n+This process installs the application dependencies defined in the application's\n+``package.json``. The most important of which is the ``@hyperledger/fabric-gateway`` Node.js package;\n+it enables an application to connect a Fabric Gateway peer and, using a specific client identity, to\n+submit and evaluate transactions, and receive events.\n \n Once ``npm install`` completes, everything is in place to run the application.\n-Let's take a look at the sample JavaScript application files we will be using\n+\n+Let's take a look at the sample TypeScript application files we will be using\n in this tutorial. Run the following command to list the files in this directory:\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+.. code-block:: bash\n \n   ls\n \n You should see the following:\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+.. code-block:: text\n \n-  app.js                  node_modules            package.json       package-lock.json\n+  dist\n+  node_modules\n+  package-lock.json\n+  package.json\n+  src\n+  tsconfig.json\n \n-.. note:: The first part of the following section involves communication with the Certificate\n-          Authority. You may find it useful to stream the CA logs when running\n-          the upcoming programs by opening a new terminal shell and running\n-          ``docker logs -f ca_org1``.\n+The ``src`` directory contains the client application source code. The JavaScript output generated from this source\n+code during the install process is located in the ``dist`` directory, and can be ignored.\n \n-When we started the Fabric test network back in the first step, an admin user --- literally called ``admin`` ---\n-was created as the **registrar** for the Certificate Authority (CA). Our first\n-step is to generate the private key, public key, and X.509 certificate for\n-``admin`` by having the application call the ``enrollAdmin`` . This process uses a **Certificate\n-Signing Request** (CSR) --- the private and public key are first generated\n-locally and the public key is then sent to the CA which returns an encoded\n-certificate for use by the application. These credentials are then stored\n-in the wallet, allowing us to act as an administrator for the CA.\n+When we started the Fabric test network back in the first step, several identities were created using the Certificate\n+Authorities. These include a user identity for each of the organizations. The application will use the credentials\n+of one of these user identities to transact with the network.\n \n Let's run the application and then step through each of the interactions with the smart contract functions. From the\n-``asset-transfer-basic/application-javascript`` directory, run the following command:\n-\n-.. code:: bash\n-\n-  node app.js\n-\n-\n-First, the application enrolls the admin user\n----------------------------------------------\n-\n-.. note:: It is important to note that enrolling the admin and registering the app user are interactions that\n-          take place between the application and the Certificate Authority, not between the application and the chaincode.\n-          If you examine the chaincode in ``asset-transfer-basic/chaincode-javascript/lib`` you will find that the chaincode\n-          does not contain any functionality that supports enrolling the admin or registering the user.\n-\n-In the sample application code below, you will see that after getting reference to the\n-common connection profile path, making sure the connection profile exists, and specifying where to create the wallet,\n-``enrollAdmin()`` is executed and the admin credentials are generated from the Certificate Authority.\n-\n-.. code:: bash\n-\n-  async function main() {\n-    try {\n-      // build an in memory object with the network configuration (also known as a connection profile)\n-      const ccp = buildCCP();\n-\n-      // build an instance of the fabric ca services client based on\n-      // the information in the network configuration\n-      const caClient = buildCAClient(FabricCAServices, ccp);\n-\n-      // setup the wallet to hold the credentials of the application user\n-      const wallet = await buildWallet(Wallets, walletPath);\n-\n- ``wallet`` directory.\n-You can find administrator's certificate and private key in the ``wallet/admin.id``\n-file.\n+``asset-transfer-basic/application-gateway-typescript`` directory, run the following command:\n \n-.. note:: If you decide to start over by taking down the network and bringing it back up again, you will\n-          have to delete the ``wallet`` folder and its identities prior to re-running the javascript application\n-          or you will get an error. This happens because the Certificate Authority and its database are taken down\n-          when the test-network is taken down but the original wallet still remains in the application-javascript directory\n-          so it must be deleted.  When you re-run the sample javascript application, a new wallet and credentials will\n-          be generated.\n+.. code-block:: bash\n \n+  npm start\n \n-If you scroll back up to the beginning of the output in your terminal, it should be similar to below:\n \n-.. code:: bash\n-\n-  Wallet path: /Users/<your_username>/fabric-samples/asset-transfer-basic/application-javascript/wallet\n-  Successfully enrolled admin user and imported it into the wallet\n-\n-Because the admin registration step is bootstrapped when the Certificate Authority\n-is started, we only need to enroll the admin.\n-\n-.. note:: Since the Fabric CA interactions are common across the samples, enrollAdmin() and the other CA\n-          related functions are included in the ``fabric-samples/test-application/javascript/CAUtil.js``\n-          common utility.\n-\n-As for the app user, we need the application to register and enroll the user in the next step.\n-\n-\n-Second, the application registers and enrolls an application user\n------------------------------------------------------------------\n+First, the application creates a gRPC connection to the Gateway peer\n+--------------------------------------------------------------------\n \n-Now that we have the administrator's credentials in a wallet, the application uses the ``admin``\n-user to register and enroll an app user which will be used\n-to interact with the blockchain network. The section of the application code is shown below.\n+The client application establishes a `gRPC <https://grpc.io/>`__ connection to the Gateway peer that it will use to\n+transact with the network. To do this it only requires the endpoint address of the Gateway peer and, if the Gateway is\n+configured to use TLS, appropriate TLS certificates to establish a secure connection. There is significant overhead\n+associated with establishing gRPC connections, so this connection should be retained by the application and shared by\n+all Gateway connections to the Gateway peer.\n+\n+.. note:: In order to maintain security of any private data used in transactions, the application should connect to a\n+          Gateway peer belonging to the same organization as the client identity. If the client identity's organization\n+          does not host any peers then a Gateway peer hosted by an upstream organization through which the client's\n+          organization is authorized to transact should be used.\n+\n+The TypeScript application creates a gRPC connection using the TLS certificate of the Certificate Authority for the\n+Gateway peer's organization, so that the authenticity of the peer's credentials can be verified. Since the Docker\n+container hosting the Gateway peer is reached at a ``localhost`` address, a gRPC option is specified to force this\n+endpoint address to be interpreted as the hostname in the peer's TLS certificate, allowing the TLS connection to be\n+successfully established.\n+\n+.. code-block:: TypeScript\n+\n+  const peerEndpoint = 'localhost:7051';\n+\n+  async function newGrpcConnection(): Promise<grpc.Client> {\n+      const tlsRootCert = await fs.readFile(tlsCertPath);\n+      const tlsCredentials = grpc.credentials.createSsl(tlsRootCert);\n+      return new grpc.Client(peerEndpoint, tlsCredentials, {\n+          'grpc.ssl_target_name_override': 'peer0.org1.example.com',\n+      });\n+  }\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+Second, the application creates a Gateway connection\n+----------------------------------------------------\n \n-  // in a real application this would be done only when a new user was required to be added\n-  // and would be part of an administrative flow\n-  await registerAndEnrollUser(caClient, wallet, mspOrg1, org1UserId, 'org1.department1');\n+The application then creates a Gateway connection, which the application uses to access any of the networks\n+(analogous to channels) accessible to the Gateway peer, and smart contracts deployed to those networks. A Gateway\n+connection requires three things:\n \n-Similar to the admin enrollment, this function uses a CSR to register and enroll ``appUser`` and\n-store its credentials alongside those of ``admin`` in the wallet. We now have\n-identities for two separate users --- ``admin`` and ``appUser`` --- that can be\n-used by our application.\n+  1. gRPC connection to the Gateway peer.\n+  2. Client identity used to transact with the network.\n+  3. Signing implementation used to generate digital signatures for the client identity.\n \n-Scrolling further down in your terminal output, you should see confirmation of the app user registration\n-similar to this:\n+In addition to the above, a hash implementation can also be specified. The default implementation will typically be\n+sufficient.\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+The sample application uses an X.509 certificate for the Org1 user identity, and a signing implementation based on the\n+corresponding private key. These credentials are created using the Org1 Certificate Authority when the test network\n+is started.\n \n-  Successfully registered and enrolled user appUser and imported it into the wallet\n+.. code-block:: TypeScript\n \n-Third, the sample application prepares a connection to the channel and smart newSigner(),\n+  });\n \n-.. note:: Our connection configuration specifies only the peer from your own Org.\n-          We tell node client sdk to use the service discovery (running on the peer),\n-          which fetches other peers that are currently online, metadata like relevant endorsement policies\n-          and any static information it would have otherwise needed to communicate with the rest of the nodes.\n-          The ``asLocalhost`` set to ``true`` tells it to connect as localhost, since our client is running on same network as the other fabric nodes.\n-          In deployments where you are not running the client on the same network as the other fabric nodes,\n-          the ``asLocalhost`` option would be set to ``false``.\n+  async function newIdentity(): Promise<Identity> {\n+      const credentials = await fs.readFile(certPath);\n+      return { mspId: 'Org1MSP', credentials };\n+  }\n \n-You will notice that in the following lines of application code, the application is getting reference\n-to the Contract using the contract name and channel name via Gateway:\n+  async function newSigner(): Promise<Signer> {\n+      const privateKeyPem = await fs.readFile(keyPath);\n+      const privateKey = crypto.createPrivateKey(privateKeyPem);\n+      return signers.newPrivateKeySigner(privateKey);\n+  }\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+Third, the application The application code snippets and invoked chaincode snippets\n-are provided for each called function, as well as the terminal output.\n+Immediately after initial deployment of the chaincode, the ledger is empty. The application uses ``submitTransaction()``\n+to invoke the chaincode ``InitLedger`` transaction function, which populates the ledger with some sample data. Behind\n+the scenes, ``submitTransaction()`` will use the Gateway peer to:\n \n-The submitTransaction() function is used to invoke the chaincode ``InitLedger`` function to populate the\n-ledger with some sample data. Under the covers, the submitTransaction() function will use service discovery\n-to find a set of required endorsing peers for the chaincode, invoke the chaincode\n-on the required number of peers, gather the chaincode endorsed results from those peers,\n-and finally submit the transaction to the ordering service.\n+  1. Endorse the transaction proposal by successfully executing the transaction function on sufficient endorsing peers\n+     to satisfy the endorsement requirements.\n+  2. Submit a transaction containing the proposal and endorsements to the ordering service to be included in a block.\n+  3. Wait for the transaction to be distributed to peers and confirm that the transaction is committed successfully,\n+     updating ledger state.\n \n-Sample application ``'InitLedger'`` call\n+Sample application ``InitLedger`` call:\n \n-.. code:: bash\n+.. code-block:: TypeScript\n \n-  // Initialize a set of asset data on the channel using the chaincode 'InitLedger' function.\n-  // This type of transaction would only be run once by an application the first time it was started after it\n-  // deployed the first time. Any updates to the chaincode deployed later would likely not need to run\n-  // an \"init\" type function.\n-  console.log('\\n--> Submit Transaction: InitLedger, function creates the initial set of Stroke GNN", "user": {"login": "lichtefeld", "id": 8626833, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjg2MjY4MzM=", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/8626833?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld", "html_url": "https://github.com/lichtefeld", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/followers", "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/following{/other_user}", "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/gists{/gist_id}", "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/starred{/owner}{/repo}", "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/subscriptions", "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/orgs", "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/repos", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/events{/privacy}", "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/lichtefeld/received_events", "type": "User", "site_admin": false}, "labels": [], "state": "open", "locked": false, "assignee": null, "assignees": [], "milestone": null, "comments": 3, "created_at": "2021-12-10T19:07:11Z", "updated_at": "2021-12-10T22:37:38Z", "closed_at": null, "author_association": "COLLABORATOR", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "@marjorief -- I\u2019ve hit a less-than-ideal outcome when using the concept learner\u2019s not-as-robust hueristics when compared to the GNN that Sheng uses. With 10 examples (assuming 1 object per scene) Sheng\u2019s system very quickly gets to 90%+ accuracy while the concept learner struggles to get 5 examples that can generalize to the same concept. Some tuning of the graph match percentage parameter has helped things (as the number of nodes in a sub-object graph is now much smaller) with the following\r\n* 90% Graph Match = Only Sphere learned (simplest object)\r\n* 75% Graph Match = Sphere & _some_ cubes\r\n* 50% Graph Match = Sphere, but now we're calling more objects spheres than we should\r\n\r\nBelow are two options, integration of a Stroke GNN into the concept learner or some more processing of features to extract additional features to consider. I prefer the route of the Stroke GNN as we know that this system is highly accurate with good data. \r\n\r\n## Integration a Stroke GNN\r\nThe basic idea is that for this idea curriculum where we only have 1 object in the scene and we guarantee it will align to the linguistic utterance then we should train Sheng\u2019s Stroke GNN and take that as an additional feature with a higher weight than the other set of available features (Essentially rely on the stroke recognition when it\u2019s highly accurate). Then we can still display the strokes as features for the differences between objects as that's the underlying features being used to make the determination.\r\n\r\n### Non-Ideal Curriculum Considerations\r\nIf we consider learning from a non-ideal curriculum (e.g. we have N objects in the scene but only one linguistic label) then we can\u2019t reliably train a single Stroke GNN. Our world-view already asserts that a cognitive learner \"knows that objects exist in the world\" so a potential extension of this assumption is \"objects must have a physical shape\". So we could have a Stroke GNN that is trained to recognize a minimal set of shape primitives (A similar set to what we previously used in P1/2). Then we\u2019d take this shape primitive information as an additional feature for the concept learner to consider. This addresses some of the heuristic concerns with stroke matching without the GNN. We\u2019d rely on pursuit to centralize on \u2018this set of strokes, shape primitive, etc\u2019 aligns to this object then we\u2019d either a) take a memory of the observed strokes or b) after reaching the confidence level begin training the concept itself directly into a high-level stroke GNN that is trying to classify straight to concept name.\r\n\r\n## Additional Heuristics\r\nSome additional heuristics to consider:\r\n* Stroke classification - Attempt to classify strokes as 'straight' or 'curved'. This provides a better metric to match on as the normalized values are not-robust to rotation (e.g. a diamond rather than a square even though these are potentially the same shape) \r\n* If strokes are 'straight' we could reverse engineer the angle between two strokes. (It's just some math to determine the angle between two vectors) -- This could improve the rationale for matching 'is_adjacent' edges.\r\n\r\nI'd need to gives these heuristics more thought as this also creates a more complicated alignment issue as we're no longer matching discrete categories but rather continuous values where the 'acceptable' range is probably the learned mean & variance from all positive examples.\r\n\r\nThoughts on these proposal?", "reactions": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/isi-vista/adam/issues/1082/reactions", "total_count": 0, "+1": 0, "-1": 0, "laugh": 0, The next lowest 8 bits represents\nwhether the configured source is actually detected or not just after\nthe register is changed for the source.\n\nCurrent implementation evaluates whole the register to detect configured\nsource. This results in failure due to the next lowest 8 bits when the\nsource is connected in advance.\n\nThis commit fixes the bug.\n\nFixes: 25784ec2d034 (\"ALSA: bebob: Add support for Focusrite Saffire/SaffirePro series\")\nCc: <stable@vger.kernel.org> # v3.16+\nSigned-off-by: Takashi Sakamoto <o-takashi@sakamocchi.jp>\nLink: https://lore.kernel.org/r/20191102150920.20367-1-o-takashi@sakamocchi.jp\nSigned-off-by: Takashi Iwai <tiwai@suse.de>\nSigned-off-by: Greg Kroah-Hartman <gregkh@linuxfoundation.org>", "distinct": true, "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/turex/siberia_hi6250_kernel/commits/0a6c53d95f5097d7a3b7ec46d757300c0eb76d3e"}, {"sha": "225aa97e3b1d5e0329759f2203d55464eb21c951", "author": {"email": "tiwai@suse.de", "name": "Takashi Iwai"}, "message": "ALSA: hda/ca0132 - Fix possible workqueue stall\n\ncommit 15c2b3cc09a31620914955cb2a89c277c18ee999 upstream.\n\nThe unsolicited event handler for the headphone jack on CA0132 codec\ndriver tries to reschedule the another delayed work with\ncancel_delayed_work_sync(). It is not very useful for any\nother use so normal users really do not need to read this file.\n\nWaiman Long has noticed that reading this file can have negative side\neffects because zone->lock is necessary for gathering data and that a)\ninterferes with the page allocator and its users and b) can lead to hard\nlockups on large machines which have very long free_list.\n\nReduce both issues by "haokexin@gmail.com", "name": "Kevin Hao"}, "message": "dump_stack: avoid the livelock of the dump_lock\n\ncommit 5cbf2fff3bba8d3c6a4d47c1754de1cf57e2b01f upstream.\n\nIn the current code, we use the atomic_cmpxchg() to serialize the output\nof the dump_stack(), but this implementation suffers the thundering herd\nproblem. "lhenriques@suse.com", "name": "Luis Henriques"}, "message": "ceph: fix use-after-free in __ceph_remove_cap()\n\ncommit ea60ed6fcf29eebc78f2ce91491e6309ee005a01 upstream.\n\nKASAN reports a use-after-free when running xfstest generic/531, with the\nfollowing trace:\n\n[  293.903362]  kasan_report+0xe/0x20\n[  293.903365]  rb_erase+0x1f/0x790\n[  293.903370]
